04240nam a22006015i 9780773589919DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735899197 a10.1515/97807735899192doi  a(DE-B1597)656205  a(OCoLC)1037901456  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aQA76.9.C66 ǂb S95 2013eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a303.48/34  aSR 850qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/143366:1 aSwirski, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Literature to Biterature :bLem, Turing, Darwin, and Explorations in Computer Literature, Philosophy of Mind, and Cultural Evolution /cPeter Swirski. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (216 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFrom Literature to Biterature -- tLemmata -- tPart One -- tBiterature -- tComputhors -- tBibliosophy -- tTranshumana -- tPart Two -- tTT -- tQED -- tToM -- tY2K+ -- tPart Three -- tHow to Make War and Assassinate People -- tBiologic, or the Philosophy of Error -- tMind Your Business -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Literature to Biterature is based on the premise that in the foreseeable future computers will become capable of creating works of literature. Among hundreds of other questions, it considers: Under which conditions would machines become capable of creative writing? Given that computer evolution will exceed the pace of natural evolution a million-fold, what will such a state of affairs entail in terms of art, culture, social life, and even nonhuman rights? Drawing a map of impending literary, cultural, social, and technological revolutions, Peter Swirski boldly assumes that computers will leap from mere syntax-driven processing to semantically rich understanding. He argues that acknowledging biterature as a species of literature will involve adopting the same range of attitudes to computer authors (computhors) as to human ones and that it will be necessary to approach them as agents with internal states and creative intentions. Ranging from the metafiction of Stanislaw Lem to the "Turing test" (familiar to scientists working in Artificial Intelligence and the philosophers of mind) to the evolutionary trends of culture and machines, Swirski's scenarios lay the groundwork for a new area of study on the cusp of literary futurology, evolutionary cognition, and philosophy of the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtificial intelligence. 0aComputers and civilization. 0aLanguage and languages -- Philosophy. 0aLiterature -- Philosophy. 0aPhilosophy of mind. 0aSocial evolution. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aMinsky, Marvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358991940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773589919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773589919/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles